WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:27.380
I mean, because, you know, you read a bunch of people, Foucault, Nietzsche, I mean, all

00:00:27.380 --> 00:00:32.980
of these thinkers have connections, but like, the lineage seems so clear to me, like, I

00:00:32.980 --> 00:00:41.440
find it almost impossible to delineate the thread or the type of thinking between some

00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:45.740
of these people, it feels like they just kind of fall into each other in productive ways,

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:51.880
not just in some sort of melange of nothingness, but like, all of the arguments or the sort

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:59.380
of impressionistic stuff in this series of lectures is like, I see that Foucault, I see

00:00:59.380 --> 00:01:03.260
that a little bit in Hegel, I for sure see it in Nietzsche.

00:01:03.260 --> 00:01:10.760
And it's funny, because Heidegger basically says that throughout the series of lectures as

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:10.760
well.

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:17.720
It's like, this is the one question of all of philosophy, and for me and for everybody, this

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:20.480
is the only question is, what does it mean to think?

00:01:20.740 --> 00:01:22.480
What does it mean to be a human being?

00:01:23.780 --> 00:01:31.220
But on the flip side, just real quick, I did find this first lecture a little bit circular,

00:01:31.220 --> 00:01:33.660
and it took me a while to kind of dig into it.

00:01:34.180 --> 00:01:38.980
You know, the style, I mean, we've critiqued his style here and there, but I found it like,

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:40.940
okay, you're saying the same thing.

00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:43.880
And I get that, you know, it's all auto referential.

00:01:43.880 --> 00:01:46.020
And that's part of the thesis, basically.

00:01:46.020 --> 00:01:50.020
But I'm like, can you try to say something else besides repeating yourself?

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:53.360
Like, just add, I don't know, just an example, anything.

00:01:53.620 --> 00:01:59.280
Like, I felt, the second one for today, I kind of dug into, I was able to get some stuff

00:01:59.280 --> 00:01:59.440
out.

00:01:59.460 --> 00:02:03.480
But the first one, it just kind of felt like it plotted, plotted along.

00:02:04.420 --> 00:02:10.100
Well, I liked it because it gave me a completely different sense of the way that he's thinking

00:02:10.100 --> 00:02:11.020
of calling here.

00:02:12.100 --> 00:02:17.200
And so, like, a lot of the sort of everyday usages of, like, what calls us to think, you

00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:20.240
know, like, I had a sense of, like, okay, this is going to meet, there's going to be

00:02:20.240 --> 00:02:24.980
the invitation, you know, what calls us to think, is calling us to become involved with

00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:25.140
it.

00:02:25.180 --> 00:02:32.240
But he had a lot of that, those kind of, like, common sort of articulations of his questions

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:38.600
where I just wasn't, I was hearing calling sort of, like, very telegraphically and not,

00:02:38.780 --> 00:02:40.760
you know, in his relationship to a naming.

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:47.240
And I kind of liked what he did with the relationship between, say, calling something a name and what

00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:48.280
calls to us.

00:02:48.620 --> 00:02:53.760
And especially, like, when he started talking about the sense of command, right?

00:02:53.820 --> 00:02:58.840
So, like, not a command as giving an order that is an imperative placed upon you, but

00:02:58.840 --> 00:03:02.440
more like an invitation or an entrustment.

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:08.520
You have been entrusted with a particular requirement to care for a particular kind of thing.

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:18.060
So, you know, it definitely helped me reorient myself to the way that he's using the call

00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:18.400
here.

00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:23.060
You know, so we're starting with, this is, you know, we're on part two of the two-part

00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:23.800
lecture series.

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:26.760
And we're just doing lecture one and lecture two.

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:31.180
And, you know, lecture one is he's sort of, like, restarting up the question, what is called

00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:31.620
thinking?

00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:37.700
Like, all right, there are four, this breaks itself up into four, you know, primary questions.

00:03:37.820 --> 00:03:44.160
What do we mean by, you know, this question or this, what thinking, what does it signify,

00:03:44.280 --> 00:03:45.640
this word thinking?

00:03:49.140 --> 00:03:54.400
What is sort of, like, commonly said or what's the traditional doctrine of what we usually mean

00:03:54.400 --> 00:03:56.680
when we talk about what thinking is?

00:03:57.100 --> 00:04:02.920
What are the sort of prerequisites that are required in order to take up the activity of

00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:03.220
thinking?

00:04:03.760 --> 00:04:10.540
And then what is calling us or what is the call itself to take up thinking?

00:04:10.680 --> 00:04:13.620
And he's, like, speculating, although it seems like it's not actually speculating.

00:04:14.180 --> 00:04:21.620
That fourth question is the privileged one insofar as it is bringing up the other three.

00:04:21.780 --> 00:04:23.100
It's involving the other three.

00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:23.820
Right.

00:04:23.920 --> 00:04:25.740
That's sort of the organizing question.

00:04:26.220 --> 00:04:32.240
And all the other questions in some way spawn from it, or they're all related, but it seems

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:33.860
like that is the sort of foundational.

00:04:33.860 --> 00:04:44.380
Because it's involving that command or compulsion or that push, that drive towards being and

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:45.300
thinking, right?

00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:51.360
It's like all the other ones are at least a little bit superficial in regard to that primary

00:04:51.360 --> 00:04:52.300
question.

00:04:53.540 --> 00:04:57.740
But it definitely, I mean, the way that he takes on call there, which, you know, he's really

00:04:57.740 --> 00:05:01.860
careful with how he uses the word command, and he doesn't, I think, want to think of it

00:05:01.860 --> 00:05:08.560
as a compulsion, that, you know, it is much more of an invitation or an entrustment.

00:05:08.660 --> 00:05:14.060
And that is a, that gives a very different flavor or character to thinking that, as opposed

00:05:14.060 --> 00:05:18.060
to, like, the what we've been, how we've been thinking of it, almost as, like, a coping

00:05:18.060 --> 00:05:20.020
mechanism, sort of, like, in that Zizek.

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:20.700
Right.

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:24.100
Well, the compulsion would be the common thinking.

00:05:24.460 --> 00:05:30.480
I think that's kind of how he treats that here, where it's like, we tend towards representational

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:37.000
thinking, because it's more convenient, because it eases communication, engagement, it just

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.720
fits into modern techno-social society better, representational thinking.

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:42.720
Right.

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:45.940
So you slide into that as a compulsion, almost.

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:52.820
And he wants to get away from that with the more essential type of thinking.

00:05:53.180 --> 00:05:59.700
Which, to me, like, and this has been an objection of John's, I think, throughout this.

00:06:00.020 --> 00:06:02.420
I'm sitting, I'm sitting quietly here, just kind of waiting.

00:06:02.420 --> 00:06:07.620
I know, because the opposition, I mean, we don't have to totally get into the weeds right

00:06:07.620 --> 00:06:08.040
up front.

00:06:08.140 --> 00:06:18.300
But, like, the opposition between common, commonness and Heideggerian-ness is, like, why, why is

00:06:18.300 --> 00:06:19.180
there that opposition?

00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:23.400
Like, it doesn't, I understand that representational thinking is a problem.

00:06:23.940 --> 00:06:32.180
That, articulating it as a problem is fine, but treating it as unnatural and as improper seems

00:06:32.180 --> 00:06:36.240
like just kind of a strange argument, if that's the way that everybody thinks.

00:06:36.740 --> 00:06:40.400
If that's the way that everybody does things, how can you call that unnatural?

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:44.020
Just by virtue of the numbers, you know?

00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:52.360
Yeah, I mean, it's interesting, because I had read this before when we were continuing, and

00:06:52.360 --> 00:06:57.620
I remember at the time reading it and being like, okay, there's the annoying return to the

00:06:57.620 --> 00:07:02.760
metaphorics of what I would just loosely call the metaphorics of authenticity or propriety

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:03.400
or whatever.

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:09.460
But it didn't bug me, because I was interested in the train going from the Nietzschean lineage

00:07:09.460 --> 00:07:14.000
not, but now we took two months off, and I read it again last night, and I'm just like,

00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:20.960
Jesus fucking Christ, like, honestly, like, I couldn't get through it without crossing out

00:07:20.960 --> 00:07:28.300
and also just the relentlessness of his desire to say, you know, it's a story of alienation

00:07:28.300 --> 00:07:34.000
that Heidegger perpetually tells, you know, which is, once we were authentically in language

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:39.760
in relation to being, and now we're not, and we've fallen out of, and so his desire is

00:07:39.760 --> 00:07:42.880
to return to the proper domain of language and all these things.

00:07:43.740 --> 00:07:49.140
And this is partly in response to the Daniel Gross stuff I read this weekend, but, like,

00:07:49.840 --> 00:07:53.580
to me, that commitment, the fascism is right there, right?

00:07:53.660 --> 00:08:01.080
Like, the notion that there is a proper relation that most people, you know, have fallen away

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:03.880
from that he wants to try to return us to.

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:12.340
Like, how is that not the basis of purity, propriety, all of the sort of deep metaphoric, and I

00:08:12.340 --> 00:08:16.460
understand that there are ways of complicating the notion of essence in these things, but

00:08:16.460 --> 00:08:21.620
everything about it seems to shout, like, we've fallen away.

00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:23.580
Like, it's a Garden of Eden story.

00:08:23.680 --> 00:08:23.900
Right.

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:24.260
Right.

00:08:24.840 --> 00:08:25.140
Pre-lapsed area.

00:08:25.140 --> 00:08:26.180
Once upon a time.

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:26.640
Right.

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:27.120
Exactly.

00:08:27.280 --> 00:08:29.880
And in this case, it's not that we were in the state of pure presence.

00:08:29.880 --> 00:08:32.300
We were in the state of pure non-presence, right?

00:08:32.420 --> 00:08:35.660
Like, and we've fallen into the state of presence and representation.

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:35.960
Right.

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:36.380
Yeah.

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:41.460
And we have to try to get back to, which, I mean, Nate, I can't agree with you more.

